{"topics":[{"topicLabel":"Linguistics: connecting words which introduce a cause or reason","topicThesaurusName":"topics","topicUrl":"http://dictionary.cambridge.org/topics/language/connecting-words-which-introduce-a-cause-or-reason/","topicId":"connecting-words-which-introduce-a-cause-or-reason","topicParentId":"language"}],"dictionaryCode":"american-english","entryContent":"<di><header><title>light<\/title><\/header> <pos-block><header><info><posgram><pos>noun<\/pos><\/posgram> <audio type=\"pronunciation\" region=\"us\"><source type=\"audio/mpeg\" src=\"https://dictionary.cambridge.org/media/american-english/us_pron/l/lig/light/light.mp3\"/><source type=\"audio/ogg\" src=\"https://dictionary.cambridge.org/media/american-english/us_pron_ogg/l/lig/light/light.ogg\"/><\/audio> <pron>/<ipa>lɑɪt<\/ipa>/<\/pron> <\/info><\/header><sense-block><header><title>ENERGY<\/title><\/header> <def-block><definition><info><lvl>\u203a<\/lvl> <gram>[<gcs><gc>C/U<\/gc><\/gcs>]<\/gram><\/info> <def>the energy from the sun or fire and from electrical devices that allows you to see clearly: <\/def><\/definition><examp><info><gram>[<gcs><gc>U<\/gc><\/gcs>]<\/gram><\/info><eg>Light was streaming through the windows.<\/eg><\/examp><examp><info><gram>[<gcs><gc>U<\/gc><\/gcs>]<\/gram><\/info><eg>The light was so bright that it hurt my eyes.<\/eg><\/examp><\/def-block> <def-block><definition><info><lvl>\u203a<\/lvl> <gram>[<gcs><gc>C/U<\/gc><\/gcs>]<\/gram><\/info> <def>A light is also anything that provides light, esp. an electric lamp: <\/def><\/definition><examp><info><gram>[<gcs><gc>C<\/gc><\/gcs>]<\/gram><\/info><eg>Don\u2019t forget to turn off the lights when you leave.<\/eg><\/examp><\/def-block> <def-block><definition><info><lvl>\u203a<\/lvl> <gram>[<gcs><gc>C/U<\/gc><\/gcs>]<\/gram><\/info> <def>A light is also a traffic light: <\/def><\/definition><examp><eg>Let\u2019s go \u2013 you\u2019ve got a green light.<\/eg><\/examp><\/def-block><\/sense-block> <sense-block><header><title>FLAME<\/title><\/header> <def-block><definition><info><lvl>\u203a<\/lvl> <gram>[<gcs><gc>U<\/gc><\/gcs>]<\/gram><\/info> <def>a device used to produce a flame, such as a match: <\/def><\/definition><examp><eg>Excuse me, have you got a light?<\/eg><\/examp><\/def-block><\/sense-block> <entry-xref>→ <lab>Idioms<\/lab> <x dictionary=\"american-english\" entryId=\"in-the-light-of\"><f>in (the) light of<\/f><\/x>, <x dictionary=\"american-english\" entryId=\"light-at-the-end-of-the-tunnel\"><f>light at the end of the tunnel<\/f><\/x><\/entry-xref><\/pos-block> <pos-block><header><info><posgram><pos>adjective<\/pos><\/posgram> <audio type=\"pronunciation\" region=\"us\"><source type=\"audio/mpeg\" src=\"https://dictionary.cambridge.org/media/american-english/us_pron/l/lig/light/light.mp3\"/><source type=\"audio/ogg\" src=\"https://dictionary.cambridge.org/media/american-english/us_pron_ogg/l/lig/light/light.ogg\"/><\/audio> <pron>/<ipa>lɑɪt<\/ipa>/<\/pron> <\/info><\/header><sense-block><header><title>NOT HEAVY<\/title><\/header> <def-block><definition><info><lvl>\u203a<\/lvl> <gram>[<gcs><gc>-er/-est only<\/gc><\/gcs>]<\/gram><\/info> <def>having little weight; not heavy: <\/def><\/definition><examp><eg>This suitcase is pretty light.<\/eg><\/examp><examp><eg>Ty\u2019s a few pounds lighter than he used to be.<\/eg><\/examp><\/def-block> <def-block><definition><info><lvl>\u203a<\/lvl> <gram>[<gcs><gc>-er/-est only<\/gc><\/gcs>]<\/gram><\/info> <def>Clothes that are light are made of thin material which allows you to be cool: <\/def><\/definition><examp><eg>a light summer dress<\/eg><\/examp><\/def-block> <def-block><definition><info><lvl>\u203a<\/lvl> <gram>[<gcs><gc>-er/-est only<\/gc><\/gcs>]<\/gram><\/info> <def>A light meal is a small one: <\/def><\/definition><examp><eg>a light snack<\/eg><\/examp><\/def-block><\/sense-block> <sense-block><header><title>NOT FAT<\/title><\/header> <def-block><definition><info><lvl>\u203a<\/lvl> <spellvar>(<lab>also<\/lab> <f>lite<\/f>)<\/spellvar><\/info> <def>(of food) having less fat or fewer calories than usual: <\/def><\/definition><examp><eg>light cream cheese<\/eg><\/examp><\/def-block><\/sense-block> <sense-block><header><title>NOT SERIOUS<\/title><\/header> <def-block><definition><info><lvl>\u203a<\/lvl> <gram>[<gcs><gc>-er/-est only<\/gc><\/gcs>]<\/gram><\/info> <def>intended to entertain; not serious: <\/def><\/definition><examp><eg>Take along some light reading for the trip.<\/eg><\/examp><\/def-block><\/sense-block> <sense-block><header><title>NOT A LOT<\/title><\/header> <def-block><definition><info><lvl>\u203a<\/lvl> <gram>[<gcs><gc>-er/-est only<\/gc><\/gcs>]<\/gram><\/info> <def>not great in strength or amount; slight: <\/def><\/definition><examp><eg>a light rain<\/eg><\/examp><examp><eg>light traffic<\/eg><\/examp><examp><eg>The doctor said it was OK to take light exercise, such as walking.<\/eg><\/examp><\/def-block> <def-block><definition><info><lvl>\u203a<\/lvl> <gram>[<gcs><gc>-er/-est only<\/gc><\/gcs>]<\/gram><\/info> <def>A light sentence in prison is a short one.<\/def><\/definition><\/def-block> <def-block><definition><info><lvl>\u203a<\/lvl> <gram>[<gcs><gc>-er/-est only<\/gc><\/gcs>]<\/gram><\/info> <def>Tastes and smells described as light are not obvious: <\/def><\/definition><examp><eg>a light scent of wildflowers<\/eg><\/examp><\/def-block> <phrase-block><header><title>light eater/drinker<\/title><\/header> <def-block><definition><info><lvl>\u203a<\/lvl> <\/info><def>A light eater/drinker eats or drinks only a little.<\/def><\/definition><\/def-block><\/phrase-block><\/sense-block> <sense-block><header><title>ENERGY<\/title><\/header> <def-block><definition><info><lvl>\u203a<\/lvl> <gram>[<gcs><gc>-er/-est only<\/gc><\/gcs>]<\/gram><\/info> <def>providing energy from the sun that allows you to see clearly: <\/def><\/definition><examp><eg>It was still light out at eight in the evening.<\/eg><\/examp><\/def-block><\/sense-block> <entry-xref>→ <lab>Idioms<\/lab> <x dictionary=\"american-english\" entryId=\"as-light-as-a-feather\"><f>(as) light as a feather<\/f><\/x><\/entry-xref><\/pos-block> <pos-block><header><info><posgram><pos>adjective<\/pos>, <pos>adverb<\/pos> <gram>[<gcs><gc>-er/-est only<\/gc><\/gcs>]<\/gram><\/posgram> <audio type=\"pronunciation\" region=\"us\"><source type=\"audio/mpeg\" src=\"https://dictionary.cambridge.org/media/american-english/us_pron/l/lig/light/light.mp3\"/><source type=\"audio/ogg\" src=\"https://dictionary.cambridge.org/media/american-english/us_pron_ogg/l/lig/light/light.ogg\"/><\/audio> <pron>/<ipa>lɑɪt<\/ipa>/<\/pron> <\/info><\/header><sense-block><header><title>PALE<\/title><\/header> <def-block><definition><info><lvl>\u203a<\/lvl> <\/info><def>(of colors) pale: <\/def><\/definition><examp><eg>a light-colored car<\/eg><\/examp><examp><eg>The walls were light green.<\/eg><\/examp><\/def-block><\/sense-block><\/pos-block> <pos-block><header><info><posgram><pos>verb<\/pos><\/posgram> <audio type=\"pronunciation\" region=\"us\"><source type=\"audio/mpeg\" src=\"https://dictionary.cambridge.org/media/american-english/us_pron/l/lig/light/light.mp3\"/><source type=\"audio/ogg\" src=\"https://dictionary.cambridge.org/media/american-english/us_pron_ogg/l/lig/light/light.ogg\"/><\/audio> <pron>/<ipa>lɑɪt<\/ipa>/<\/pron> <irreg-infls>(<inf-group><lab>past tense and past participle<\/lab> <f>lit<\/f>  <pron>/<ipa>lɪt<\/ipa>/<\/pron> or <f>lighted<\/f><\/inf-group>)<\/irreg-infls><\/info><\/header> <sense-block><header><title>ENERGY<\/title><\/header> <def-block><definition><info><lvl>\u203a<\/lvl> <gram>[<gcs><gc>T<\/gc><\/gcs>]<\/gram><\/info> <def>to provide with energy from the sun, fire, or electrical devices that allow you to see clearly: <\/def><\/definition><examp><eg>The house was lit with candles for the dinner party.<\/eg><\/examp><\/def-block><\/sense-block> <sense-block><header><title>FLAME<\/title><\/header> <def-block><definition><info><lvl>\u203a<\/lvl> <gram>[<gcs><gc>I/T<\/gc><\/gcs>]<\/gram><\/info> <def>to produce a flame: <\/def><\/definition><examp><info><gram>[<gcs><gc>I<\/gc><\/gcs>]<\/gram><\/info><eg>I can\u2019t get the barbecue to light.<\/eg><\/examp><examp><info><gram>[<gcs><gc>T<\/gc><\/gcs>]<\/gram><\/info><eg>I tried to light the fire, but the wood was wet.<\/eg><\/examp><\/def-block><\/sense-block> <entry-xref>→ <lab>Idioms<\/lab> <x dictionary=\"american-english\" entryId=\"light-a-fire-under-someone\"><f>light a fire under <i>someone<\/i><\/f><\/x><\/entry-xref> <entry-xref>→ <lab>Phrasal verbs<\/lab> <x dictionary=\"american-english\" entryId=\"light-up\"><f>light up<\/f><\/x>, <x dictionary=\"american-english\" entryId=\"light-up-something\"><f>light up <i>something<\/i><\/f><\/x><\/entry-xref><\/pos-block><footer><copyright>(Definition of light  from the <x href=\"https://dictionary.cambridge.org/dictionary/american-english/\" title=\"Cambridge Academic Content Dictionary\n\">Cambridge Academic Content Dictionary\n<\/x> © Cambridge University Press)<\/copyright><\/footer><\/di>\n","entryLabel":"light","entryUrl":"http://dictionary.cambridge.org/dictionary/american-english/light","format":"xml","entryId":"light"}